# Deploying {{ project_name }} to a server or another machine

The single source of truth for standing this project up somewhere new (a lab server, a
collaborator's PC, an offline analysis box). Code + inputs travel through git; **two things
are machine-specific and never committed** — set them up here:

- **`config.yml`** — where the connected/external data lives on *this* machine (a copy of
  `config.example.yml`).
- **`.env`** — secrets / API keys (a copy of `.env.example`).

Everything under `data/derived/`, `_targets/`, and the agent caches is **regenerable** — it
is rebuilt from inputs + code, never transferred.

## Option A — clone (the target has git + network)

```bash
git clone <repo-url> {{ project_slug }}
cd {{ project_slug }}
cp config.example.yml config.yml     # then edit: point each data_sources[*].path at this machine
cp .env.example .env                 # then edit: fill in any API keys / secrets
```
{% if analysis_stack != 'none' %}
Connect the external data (junction recipe below), then build:

```bash
python scripts/bundle.py --verify    # check every config.yml data path exists
make setup && make all               # restore the environment + run the full pipeline
make check                           # lint + tests + placeholder scan
```
{% endif %}
## Option B — offline bundle (the target has no git/internet)

On a machine that already has the repo, build a clean snapshot and copy it over:

```bash
python scripts/bundle.py             # or: make bundle
# -> writes dist/{{ project_slug }}-<shortsha>.tar.gz (committed tree only; config.yml,
#    .env, data/derived/, _targets/ and caches are all excluded automatically)
```

Transfer the tarball, then on the target:

```bash
mkdir {{ project_slug }} && tar -xzf <bundle>.tar.gz -C {{ project_slug }} && cd {{ project_slug }}
cp config.example.yml config.yml && cp .env.example .env   # then edit both
```
{% if analysis_stack != 'none' %}
Connect the data (below) and `make setup && make all`, exactly as in Option A.

## Connect the external data (junction / symlink)

`config.yml` points at a data root that is **not** copied into the repo. Link it so paths
resolve without hard-coding absolutes in code:

- **Windows (cmd):** `mklink /J data\external "D:\path\to\data-root"`
- **Windows (PowerShell):** `New-Item -ItemType Junction -Path data\external -Target "D:\path\to\data-root"`
- **Linux / macOS:** `ln -s /path/to/data-root data/external`

Point each `config.yml` `data_sources[*].path` at a location under `data/external/` (or the
mount directly), then re-run `python scripts/bundle.py --verify` until every source is `OK`.
{% endif %}
## What NOT to commit

`config.yml` and `.env` are git-ignored on purpose — they differ on every machine. Never
commit them; never hard-code an absolute path in code (read it from `config.yml`).

